If we re-set assumptions about abortion and apply them to all human beings, what emerges is a stark version of one of several stray rabbits that wobble in and out of my yard.

Confronting spiritual abortion in our medicinal beliefs

Throughout the medical history, changes in cultural, social, political, economic and religious views lent fertile ground for the retreat of medical truths in favor of incompatible sets of dogmas – both in the East and West.

The falsehoods relating to woman and abortion have been ingrained in the conservative medical literatures of both the East and the West. It is usually a withdrawal from morality. Just as Galenic concepts of physiology allowed for considerable variations to the non-essentials for life (“partials as sufficiency”), absence of these would suffice for the death of an embryo. The transition from the medieval is not devoid of differences, yet not devoid of notable similarities. For example, Aristotle’s writings, which received a more permanent place in the Medieval Semenology in the second century, appears to have influenced Hippocratic time-honored concepts of procreation and the establishment of the newborn.
